    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-11-15T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-11-15T10:00:00-05:00" n="694"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d694">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/6697: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Diplomatic Agent and Consul General at Tangier</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">White</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tangier</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-15T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 15, 1940—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 15—2:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>61. Referring to my 39, October 28, 7 p.m., I hear that Weygand’s reception of
                    the Churchill messages was non-committal but not hostile. He evinced particular
                    interest in the question of what armed assistance Great Britain could supply in
                    case he turned activist (as a premature Tangier rumor, presumably based on radio
                    broadcast, claims that he may).</p>
                <p>I heard also that Weygand has agreed to collaborate with the Count de Paris<note
                        n="90" xml:id="d694fn90">Bourbon-Orléans Royalist Pretender.</note> but am
                    ignorant as to whether this signifies a definite royalist orientation on his
                    part. My informant questioned whether De Gaulle and Weygand could work together
                    cordially.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">White</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
